If your dog is prone to ripping things up, this probably is not the game for you.

If your dog gets overstimulated by the game, stop playing, and let them calm down. Never push your dog to play. Let them choose. Respect your dog's "No".

Occasionally, 1 dog will be the Blanket Monster and "attack" your other dog through the blanket.

This could result in a long play session for your dogs. It's a great game to play indoors when the weather is bad.

After about 30 minutes, my boys will be tired and go nap.

During either these 2 ways, my dogs will 'play bite', i.e. mouth me through the blanket w/ a little pressure. If they use too much pressure, cry out in exaggerated pain to let them know that was too far.

B. Throw the blanket over your dog's head. They are the Blanket Monster.

Rough house with them a bit, if you are comfortable. This way requires more trust between you and your dog.

I usually play one of 2 ways:
A. Move your hand on the couch & under the blanket like a little scurrying rodent. You are the Blanket Monster. 

This will elicit your dog's prey drive. Let them "catch" you a couple of times.
#DogGames

If you have a dog and you're looking for another game to play with them, I highly recommend "Blanket Monster". It's a game that can be played with a human & 1 or 2 dogs.

Materials required: an old towel or blanket that won't rip easily, one you don't value #dogEnrichment

It was there that I fileted and prepped all kinds of marine life for cooking. This sometimes involved gutting wild fish, fresh from the Gulf of Mexico. I marveled at the last meals they ate & prided myself on my knife skills.
I did that for 4 years.

FF to 2016 when I got a job in the meat & seafood department of a supermarket. I really wanted to pursue an apprenticeship as a meat cutter and maybe become a whole animal butcher, but due to industry sexism, I was placed in the seafood department.

Thus began my fascination with the form and function of various bones in various species' skeletons. Even after I stopped pursuing an anthropology degree, I still liked to collect animal bones/teeth if I found them on a hike or some fortuitously fresh roadkill.

FF to taking a #zooarchaeology class at MTSU in 2010, really taking to heart my prof's suggestion to pick up dead animals on the side of the road to skeletonize & study bone structure/shape at home to become better at species ID. Shout out to @TetZoo for that guide on his sciblog
Then in senior year of my human anatomy class, we dissected sheep's eyes and I think fetal pigs. I'm not sure about the last part because I had some messy stuff happening in my life at the time.
Then in freshman year of HS (ca 2004) my biology class also did dissections. I remember feeling confident in my ability to wield a scalpel. We covered crayfish, grasshoppers, and frogs.
I think that memory stuck with me bc of the visuals of separating flesh from bodily organs & that overpowering scent of formaldehyde.

In my Biology 2 class today, we'll be starting on dissections, beginning with earthworms. I remember the 1st time I ever dissected a worm. It was in 7th grade (ca 2003) in Mr Haney's science class at Meigs Magnet Middle School. We also dissected frogs in that class.

Today's #ShowerThoughts: I have an extraordinary amount of experience in cutting up creatures and looking at their insides for someone who doesn't have a college degree.

Until I learned about my autism and my paradigm shifted.

Blame. Negative self talk. Wondering why I was born so broken, why I felt and behaved so different than everyone else.

Then I'd recover eventually and bounce back up to try another strategy to make me "successful" like the other people my age.

My internalized ableism made me determined to *show* everyone that I could do whatever they did even if my brain didn't come with the same factory settings as a typical person's.

Guess what happened when I inevitably failed at accomplishing neurotypical standards?

It was only after I learned that I'm autistic that I gave myself permission to make my life easier for myself.
